Introduction

In this notebook, we aim to analyze customer feedback from Amazon US Customer Reviews using topic modeling techniques. The objective is to extract and visualize common themes and topics within the reviews, which can provide valuable insights into customer sentiments and preferences. These insights can be utilized to enhance product features, improve customer satisfaction, and inform marketing strategies.

def select_file():
    root = tk.Tk()  # Create the root Tkinter window
    root.withdraw()  # Hide the root window so it doesn't appear
    root.attributes('-topmost', True)  # Ensure the root window is on top of all other windows
    file_paths = filedialog.askopenfilenames(parent=root)  # Open a file dialog and allow multiple file selections
    if file_paths:  # Check if any files were selected
        return file_paths  # Return the list of selected file paths
    else:
        return None  # Return None if no files were selected

file_paths = select_file()  # Call the select_file function and store the result in file_paths

Defining Data Loading and Preprocessing Functions

load_data loads the data from a file. preprocess_text cleans the text by removing non-alphabetic characters, converting to lowercase, removing stopwords, and lemmatizing the words. The example usage demonstrates loading and preprocessing the first selected file and prints the first few rows of the DataFrame.

In[21]:
def load_data(file_path):
    # Load a tab-separated CSV file and skip lines with errors
    return pd.read_csv(file_path, sep='\t', on_bad_lines='skip')

def preprocess_text(text):
    # Check if the input text is a string
    if isinstance(text, str):
        text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z]', ' ', text) # Replace non-alphabetic characters with a space
        text = text.lower() # Convert the text to lowercase
        stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english')) | {'br'} # Define stopwords and add 'br' to the set of stopwords
        words = text.split() # Split the text into words
        words = [word for word in words if word not in stop_words] # Remove stopwords from the list of words
        lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()  # Initialize the lemmatizer
        # Lemmatize each word in the list of words
        words = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in words]
        # Join the words back into a single string and return
        return " ".join(words)
    else:
        
        return "" # If the input text is not a string, return an empty string

Process the File and Perform Topic Modeling

This function preprocesses the data and performs LDA topic modeling. It prints the top words for each topic to help interpret the topics. It processes the first selected file and stores the returned variables for further use.

In[22]:
def process_file(file_path):
    # Load the data from the given file path
    df = load_data(file_path)
    # Keep only the 'review_body' column and drop rows with missing values
    df = df[['review_body']].dropna()
    # Apply the preprocess_text function to each entry in 'review_body' and store the results in 'cleaned_review'
    df['cleaned_review'] = df['review_body'].apply(preprocess_text)

    # Split the cleaned text into individual words for each review
    text_data = [text.split() for text in df['cleaned_review']]
    # Create a dictionary representation of the text data
    dictionary = corpora.Dictionary(text_data)
    # Convert the text data into bag-of-words format
    corpus = [dictionary.doc2bow(text) for text in text_data]

    num_topics = 5 # Set the number of topics to be generated by the LDA model
    ldamodel = models.LdaModel(corpus, num_topics=num_topics, id2word=dictionary, passes=1)  # Train the LDA model using the corpus and dictionary, specifying the number of topics
    topics = ldamodel.print_topics(num_words=5)# Print the top 5 words in each topic
    for topic in topics:
        print(topic)

    # Return the processed data and models
    return df, text_data, dictionary, corpus, ldamodel, num_topics

if file_paths:  # Check if there are any file paths in the file_paths list

Generate Word Clouds for Each Topic

This cell generates word clouds for each topic. Word clouds visually represent the most important words for each topic, with larger words indicating higher importance.

In[31]:
def generate_wordclouds(ldamodel, num_topics):
  
    # Create a figure with a grid of subplots
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, num_topics, figsize=(num_topics * 5, 5), squeeze=False)

    for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flatten()):
        topic_words = dict(ldamodel.show_topic(i, 100))  # Get the top 100 words for the topic
        wordcloud = WordCloud(width=400, height=400,
                              background_color='white',
                              stopwords=stopwords.words('english'),
                              min_font_size=10).generate_from_frequencies(topic_words)  # Generate word cloud

        ax.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')  # Display the word cloud
        ax.axis("off")  # Hide axes
        ax.set_title(f"Topic {i}")  # Set title

    plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust the layout
    plt.show()  # Show the plot

# Generate word clouds for the topics
generate_wordclouds(ldamodel, num_topics)

Distribution of Document Word Counts by Dominant Topic

This cell plots the distribution of word counts for documents where each topic is dominant. It helps in understanding the length of documents associated with each topic.

In[36]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

def plot_word_count_distribution(ldamodel, corpus, text_data, num_topics, max_docs=None, bins=20, color='purple'):
    
    # Initialize a dictionary to store word counts by dominant topic
    topic_word_counts = {i: [] for i in range(num_topics)}

    # Limit the number of documents processed if max_docs is specified
    if max_docs:
        corpus = corpus[:max_docs]
        text_data = text_data[:max_docs]

    # Iterate over each document in the corpus
    for doc_id, doc in enumerate(corpus):
        # Get the topics for the document with their probabilities
        doc_topics = ldamodel.get_document_topics(doc, minimum_probability=0)
        # Sort the topics by probability in descending order
        doc_topics = sorted(doc_topics, key=lambda x: -x[1])
        # Get the dominant topic for the document
        dominant_topic, _ = doc_topics[0]
        # Get the word count for the document
        word_count = len(text_data[doc_id])
        # Append the word count to the corresponding topic's list
        topic_word_counts[dominant_topic].append(word_count)

    # Plot the distribution of word counts for each topic
    for i in range(num_topics):
        plt.figure(figsize=(7, 4))  # Adjusted figure size for better visualization
        sns.histplot(topic_word_counts[i], bins=bins, kde=True, color=color)  # Plot histogram with KDE and specified color
        plt.title(f'Distribution of Document Word Counts for Topic {i}', fontsize=16)  # Set title with larger font size
        plt.xlabel('Word Count', fontsize=14)  # Set x-axis label with larger font size
        plt.ylabel('Number of Documents', fontsize=14)  # Set y-axis label with larger font size
        plt.grid(True)  # Add grid for better readability
        plt.show()  # Show the plot

# Example usage
plot_word_count_distribution(ldamodel, corpus, text_data, num_topics, max_docs=1000, bins=20, color='purple')

Plot Topic Distribution Across All Documents

This cell plots the distribution of topics across all documents. It shows how prevalent each topic is within the dataset.

In[37]:
def plot_topic_distribution(ldamodel, corpus, num_topics):
    topic_distribution = [max(ldamodel[corpus[i]], key=lambda x: x[1])[0] for i in range(len(corpus))]
    sns.histplot(topic_distribution, bins=num_topics, kde=False, discrete=True)
    plt.title('Topic Distribution Across All Documents')
    plt.xlabel('Topic')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Documents')
    plt.xticks(range(num_topics))
    plt.show()

plot_topic_distribution(ldamodel, corpus, num_topics)

Compute and Plot Coherence Scores

This cell calculates and plots the coherence scores for different numbers of topics. Coherence scores help determine the optimal number of topics by measuring how interpretable the topics are.

In[14]:
def plot_coherence_scores(dictionary, corpus, text_data):
    coherence_values = []
    topic_range = range(2, 10)
    for num in topic_range:
        model = models.LdaModel(corpus, num_topics=num, id2word=dictionary, passes=1)
        coherence_model = CoherenceModel(model=model, texts=text_data, dictionary=dictionary, coherence='c_v')
        coherence_values.append(coherence_model.get_coherence())

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(topic_range, coherence_values, marker='o')
    plt.title('Coherence Scores by Number of Topics')
    plt.xlabel('Number of Topics')
    plt.ylabel('Coherence Score')
    plt.xticks(topic_range)
    plt.show()

plot_coherence_scores(dictionary, corpus, text_data)

Compute and Visualize TF-IDF Heatmap

This cell computes the TF-IDF scores for the top 50 terms in the dataset. It visualizes these scores using a heatmap, showing the importance of terms across different documents.

In[19]:
def plot_tfidf_heatmap(df):
    cleaned_reviews = df['cleaned_review'].tolist()
    vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=50)
    tfidf_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(cleaned_reviews).toarray()
    terms = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
    tfidf_df = pd.DataFrame(tfidf_matrix, columns=terms)

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    sns.heatmap(tfidf_df.T, cmap='YlGnBu', cbar=True)
    plt.title('TF-IDF Scores for Top 50 Terms')
    plt.xlabel('Document Index')
    plt.ylabel('Term')
    plt.show()

plot_tfidf_heatmap(df)

Bar Plot of Top Words for Each Topic

This cell creates bar plots for the top terms in each topic, showing their relative importance (weights). These bar plots provide a clear comparison of the most significant words associated with each topic

In[16]:
def plot_top_terms(ldamodel, num_topics):
    for i in range(num_topics):
        topic_words = ldamodel.show_topic(i, 10)
        words = [word for word, _ in topic_words]
        weights = [weight for _, weight in topic_words]

        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
        sns.barplot(x=weights, y=words, hue=words, palette='viridis', dodge=False)
        plt.title(f'Top Terms for Topic {i}')
        plt.xlabel('Weight')
        plt.ylabel('Term')
        plt.show()

plot_top_terms(ldamodel, num_topics)
